<p>I define a variable holding an empty object before pushing elements into it in an <code>each</code> loop (or other types of loop) like so:</p>  <pre><code>foo = [] collection.each do |item|   foo &lt;&lt; item end foo </code></pre>  <p>or like this:</p>  <pre><code>foo = [] count = 0 collection.each do |item|   count += 1   raise ArgumentError if count &gt; 10   foo &lt;&lt; item end foo </code></pre>  <p>However, <code>foo</code> or <code>count</code> appears too often and clutters the code. Is there a method to shorten this chunk of code? I want to believe that the first <code>foo</code> can be placed inside the loop to run once.</p>